Both parties in either kind os adoption must be cives, and the adoptet, os course, must be sui iuris. ln the parallel passage of Gaius (i. 98, 99) adrogation is said to take place populi auctoritate, and the term is ex- plained : ⁸ quod et is qui adoptat rogatur, id est, interrogatur an velit eum quem adoptaturus sit iustum sibi filium esse, et is qui adoptatur rogatur an id fieri patiatur, et populus rogatur an id fieri iubeat.’ Adrogation was originally effected‚ after a preliminary inquiry by the pontifices, in the comitia curiata, by a legislative act of that assembly: subsequently the thirty curiae dwindled down to thirty lictors, who represented the authority os the people, and at some time aster Gaius the form was superseded by imperial rescript (⁴ perinde valet . . . ac si per populum facta esset ’ Diocletian and Maximian in Cod. 8. 48. 2); instead of the preliminary pontifical inquiry there was an investigation by a magis- trate thereto commissioned by the Emperor, os which the main purpose was the protection of the person to be adrogated‚ especially against the danger os adoption by some one much poorer than himself, whose motive might be mere avarice : ⁴ adrogationes non temere ‘nec inexplorate corn- mittuntur.
